{"docstore/ref_doc_info": {"27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719": {"node_ids": ["b2c614c7-5a4f-49b7-9ea6-bf395bd55e4a", "d507f61b-5023-4281-b391-f307985b8589", "a21ef176-da5c-464d-b043-b4614032a257", "43b76dd5-4d0d-43ef-a5ae-cabdb80b8b7e", "41ab694d-c48b-4b70-9faa-d59aa3a2b8c9", "99e39dc0-2dfa-4377-8f7e-8a7ce0b792ea", "8e704f6c-b646-4592-98c9-a36466bee519", "16b78467-e01b-4288-a6a0-89bc0a189b4d", "a84b766a-d924-4e16-8f86-56e44cce04d6", "8bc1d84e-c845-4932-8a75-ba880041369c", "31ebbf3c-4ea2-481f-8381-ad1d3364123d", "3dbeea70-1fe1-40e3-b6dd-9e4744c5136a", "c481815f-022a-4a32-b019-c45014083c39", "5541084f-5829-4efd-b2a7-6d4702865018", "b080d58f-fbb4-4028-8161-39a1e83fec14", "c4b3844f-ef6d-487a-882b-372ddaaf8bf0"], "metadata": {}}}, "docstore/data": {"b2c614c7-5a4f-49b7-9ea6-bf395bd55e4a": {"__data__": {"id_": "b2c614c7-5a4f-49b7-9ea6-bf395bd55e4a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "d507f61b-5023-4281-b391-f307985b8589", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "3f38603e963b52ecc4bce331dc7eeb04972fbd35f6b856d0f2e273d5da297599", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "E\ufb03cient Calculation of Bigram Frequencies in a Corpus of Short Texts\n\nMelvyn Drag, Gauthaman Vasudevan\nAvlino, Inc. Holdmel, NJ\n\nAbstract\n\nWe show that an e ffi cient and popular method for calculating bigram frequencies is unsuitable for bodies of short texts and o ff er a simple alternative.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 294, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d507f61b-5023-4281-b391-f307985b8589": {"__data__": {"id_": "d507f61b-5023-4281-b391-f307985b8589", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "b2c614c7-5a4f-49b7-9ea6-bf395bd55e4a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "77b18b3e42ae627d7177fc8bd343345f713c1090963b3580245310358e927403", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "a21ef176-da5c-464d-b043-b4614032a257", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "3059e3a5c2ee07d683430e5962441d579bec1abfc30649130aad20a6a4da3537", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Our method has the same computational complexity as the old method and o ff ers an exact count instead of an approximation.Keywords: NLP, Machine Learning\n\n1. Acknowledgements\n\nThis short note is the result of a brief conversation between the authors and Joel Nothman. We came across a potential problem, he gave a sketch of a fix, and we worked out the details of a solution.\n\n2.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 295, "end_char_idx": 675, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a21ef176-da5c-464d-b043-b4614032a257": {"__data__": {"id_": "a21ef176-da5c-464d-b043-b4614032a257", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "d507f61b-5023-4281-b391-f307985b8589", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "3f38603e963b52ecc4bce331dc7eeb04972fbd35f6b856d0f2e273d5da297599", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "43b76dd5-4d0d-43ef-a5ae-cabdb80b8b7e", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a483f2aac548a6473edc5e9504de9b11a0d82d97d2e28678c2fd30c3afa6cce4", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Calculating Bigram Frequecies\n\nA common task in natural language processing is to find the most frequently occurring word pairs in a text(s) in the expectation that these pairs will shed some light on the main ideas of the text, or o ff er insight into the structure of the language. One might be interested in pairings of adjacent words, but in some cases one is also interested in pairs of words in some small neighborhood.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 676, "end_char_idx": 1101, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "43b76dd5-4d0d-43ef-a5ae-cabdb80b8b7e": {"__data__": {"id_": "43b76dd5-4d0d-43ef-a5ae-cabdb80b8b7e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "a21ef176-da5c-464d-b043-b4614032a257", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "3059e3a5c2ee07d683430e5962441d579bec1abfc30649130aad20a6a4da3537", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "41ab694d-c48b-4b70-9faa-d59aa3a2b8c9", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "b21a61ef597430a09574332f34021b705e40da7237af370dc1ec0b421a1a0e26", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "The neighborhood is usually refered to as a window, and to illustrate the concept consider the following text and bigram set:\nText: \u201cI like kitties and doggies\u201d Window: 2 Bigrams: { (I like), (like kitties), (kitties and), (and doggies) }\nand this one:", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1104, "end_char_idx": 1356, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "41ab694d-c48b-4b70-9faa-d59aa3a2b8c9": {"__data__": {"id_": "41ab694d-c48b-4b70-9faa-d59aa3a2b8c9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "43b76dd5-4d0d-43ef-a5ae-cabdb80b8b7e", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a483f2aac548a6473edc5e9504de9b11a0d82d97d2e28678c2fd30c3afa6cce4", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "99e39dc0-2dfa-4377-8f7e-8a7ce0b792ea", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a63d619310404db4cc2ee41fc20473e3bb0ca9a47b1df38061a06720b8bb30d2", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Text: \u201cI like kitties and doggies\u201d Window: 4 Bigrams: { (I like), (I kitties), (I and), (like kitties), (like and), (like doggies), (kitties and), (kitties doggies), (and doggies) } .\n\n3.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1359, "end_char_idx": 1546, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "99e39dc0-2dfa-4377-8f7e-8a7ce0b792ea": {"__data__": {"id_": "99e39dc0-2dfa-4377-8f7e-8a7ce0b792ea", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "41ab694d-c48b-4b70-9faa-d59aa3a2b8c9", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "b21a61ef597430a09574332f34021b705e40da7237af370dc1ec0b421a1a0e26", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "8e704f6c-b646-4592-98c9-a36466bee519", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "1fa262568d9bf7d450a6c5575a74a72d360a9ba9257a36016833e38ebf9527c2", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "The Popular Approximation\n\nBigram frequencies are often calculated using the approximation\nf req( \u2217 , word) = f req(word , \u2217 ) = f req(word) (1)\nIn a much cited paper, Church and Hanks [2] use \u2018 = \u2019 in place of \u2018 \u2248 \u2019 because the approximation is so good.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1547, "end_char_idx": 1801, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8e704f6c-b646-4592-98c9-a36466bee519": {"__data__": {"id_": "8e704f6c-b646-4592-98c9-a36466bee519", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "99e39dc0-2dfa-4377-8f7e-8a7ce0b792ea", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a63d619310404db4cc2ee41fc20473e3bb0ca9a47b1df38061a06720b8bb30d2", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "16b78467-e01b-4288-a6a0-89bc0a189b4d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a3b5e2101b49c64fc8a2a07a3c6ede8ef90a128b545669c71083d4d17ecaceba", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Indeed, this approximation will only cause errors for the very few words which occur near the beginning or the end of the text.Preprint submitted to arXiv\n\n\nSeptember 12, 2021\nTake for example the text appearing above - the bigram (doggies, *) does not occur once, but the approximation says it does.An e ffi cient method for computing the contingency matrix for a bigram (word1, word2) is suggested by the approximation.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1802, "end_char_idx": 2223, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "16b78467-e01b-4288-a6a0-89bc0a189b4d": {"__data__": {"id_": "16b78467-e01b-4288-a6a0-89bc0a189b4d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "8e704f6c-b646-4592-98c9-a36466bee519", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "1fa262568d9bf7d450a6c5575a74a72d360a9ba9257a36016833e38ebf9527c2", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "a84b766a-d924-4e16-8f86-56e44cce04d6", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "7ccdc751787c605c738570ae4ff8821ee2697f8ebdb72213c77fa61cbfb5b723", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Store f req(w1 , w2) for all bigrams (w1 , w2) and the frequencies of all words.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 2224, "end_char_idx": 2304, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a84b766a-d924-4e16-8f86-56e44cce04d6": {"__data__": {"id_": "a84b766a-d924-4e16-8f86-56e44cce04d6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "16b78467-e01b-4288-a6a0-89bc0a189b4d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "a3b5e2101b49c64fc8a2a07a3c6ede8ef90a128b545669c71083d4d17ecaceba", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "8bc1d84e-c845-4932-8a75-ba880041369c", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "acb6977659f3ac4b9d1fb4953037dfe200d951f54e6e10fd472527bd8320d16b", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Then,\n\n\u2022 f req(word1 , word2) is known,\n\n\u2022 f req( \u223c word1 ,\n\n word2) \u2248 f req(word2) - f req(word1 , word2),\n\n\u2022 f req(word1 ,\n\n \u223c word2) \u2248 f req(word1) - f req(word1 , word2),\n\n\u2022 and f req( \u223c word1 , \u223c word2) is easily computed.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 2305, "end_char_idx": 2532, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8bc1d84e-c845-4932-8a75-ba880041369c": {"__data__": {"id_": "8bc1d84e-c845-4932-8a75-ba880041369c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "a84b766a-d924-4e16-8f86-56e44cce04d6", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "7ccdc751787c605c738570ae4ff8821ee2697f8ebdb72213c77fa61cbfb5b723", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "31ebbf3c-4ea2-481f-8381-ad1d3364123d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "d8e44efeb842493b2fe64d698df56cfcd282d1e896b4868fcf5947e64d3ef8f7", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "The statistical importance of miscalculations due to this method diminishes as our text grows larger and larger. Interest is growing in the analysis of small texts, however, and a means of computing bigrams for this type of corpus must be employed. This approximation is implemented in popular NLP libraries and can be seen in many tutorials across the internet. People who use this code, or write their own software, must know when it is appropriate.\n\n4.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 2534, "end_char_idx": 2989, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "31ebbf3c-4ea2-481f-8381-ad1d3364123d": {"__data__": {"id_": "31ebbf3c-4ea2-481f-8381-ad1d3364123d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "8bc1d84e-c845-4932-8a75-ba880041369c", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "acb6977659f3ac4b9d1fb4953037dfe200d951f54e6e10fd472527bd8320d16b", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "3dbeea70-1fe1-40e3-b6dd-9e4744c5136a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "ee95e7dbb774426866397609c3553b6639a9feb13009ada395c4b3ce8004a4ab", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "An Alternative Method\n\nWe propose an alternative. As before, store the frequencies of words and the frequencies of bigrams, but this time store two additional maps called too far left and too far right, of the form { word : list of o ff ending indices of word } . The o ff ending indices are those that are either too far to the left or too far to the right for approximation (1) to hold.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 2990, "end_char_idx": 3378, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3dbeea70-1fe1-40e3-b6dd-9e4744c5136a": {"__data__": {"id_": "3dbeea70-1fe1-40e3-b6dd-9e4744c5136a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "31ebbf3c-4ea2-481f-8381-ad1d3364123d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "d8e44efeb842493b2fe64d698df56cfcd282d1e896b4868fcf5947e64d3ef8f7", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "c481815f-022a-4a32-b019-c45014083c39", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "7f6494b6d689ec723837f8ecbbc56c4209162ba5e61db8276008cc708561828d", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "All four of these structures are built during the construction of a bigram finder, and do not cripple performance when computing statistical measures since maps are queried in O(1) time.As an example of the contents of the new maps, in \u201cDogs are better than cats\u201d, too far left[\u2018dog\u2019] = [0] for all windows.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 3381, "end_char_idx": 3688, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c481815f-022a-4a32-b019-c45014083c39": {"__data__": {"id_": "c481815f-022a-4a32-b019-c45014083c39", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "3dbeea70-1fe1-40e3-b6dd-9e4744c5136a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "ee95e7dbb774426866397609c3553b6639a9feb13009ada395c4b3ce8004a4ab", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "5541084f-5829-4efd-b2a7-6d4702865018", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "67485c1971986eeeec271eb2a844244689e032caecf4a4c88abda4026a69100c", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "In \u201ceight mice eat eight cheese sticks\u201d with window 5, too far left[\u2018eight\u2019] = [0,3]. For ease of computation the indices stored in too far right are transformed before storage using:\nc idx = length \u2212 idx \u2212 1 = g(idx) (2)\nwhere length is the length of the small piece of text being analyzed.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 3691, "end_char_idx": 3982, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5541084f-5829-4efd-b2a7-6d4702865018": {"__data__": {"id_": "5541084f-5829-4efd-b2a7-6d4702865018", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "c481815f-022a-4a32-b019-c45014083c39", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "7f6494b6d689ec723837f8ecbbc56c4209162ba5e61db8276008cc708561828d", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "b080d58f-fbb4-4028-8161-39a1e83fec14", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "66a374311d103509ba288d4691871d76162f6725ee45038df17d774d16fbf012", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "Then, too far right[\u2018cats\u2019] = [g(4) = idx] = [0 = c idx].Now, to compute the exact number of occurrences of a bigram we do the computation:\nf req( \u2217 , word) = (w \u2212 1) \u2217 word f d[word] \u2212 N X i = 1 (w \u2212 t f l[word][i] \u2212 1) (3)", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 3985, "end_char_idx": 4209, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b080d58f-fbb4-4028-8161-39a1e83fec14": {"__data__": {"id_": "b080d58f-fbb4-4028-8161-39a1e83fec14", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "5541084f-5829-4efd-b2a7-6d4702865018", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "67485c1971986eeeec271eb2a844244689e032caecf4a4c88abda4026a69100c", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "c4b3844f-ef6d-487a-882b-372ddaaf8bf0", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "f1bbcaa379334619427045ad0b2c1393e27987a7064479d3a59fc871a0677787", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "where w is the window size being searched for bigrams, w f d is a frequency distribution of all words in the corpus, t f l is the map too far left and N is the number of occurrences of the word in a position too far left.The computation of f req(word , \u2217 ) can now be performed in the same way by simply substituting t f l with t f r thanks to transformation g, which reverses the indexing.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 4212, "end_char_idx": 4602, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c4b3844f-ef6d-487a-882b-372ddaaf8bf0": {"__data__": {"id_": "c4b3844f-ef6d-487a-882b-372ddaaf8bf0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a3eb9573273d331cd7e80905eb13c97ab3cb7f46313cd4dfa7418a5fd7028de", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "b080d58f-fbb4-4028-8161-39a1e83fec14", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "66a374311d103509ba288d4691871d76162f6725ee45038df17d774d16fbf012", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "References\n\n[1] S. Bird, E. Klein, and E. Loper,\n\n Natural Language Processing With Python, 1st ed., O\u2019Reilly Media, Inc., 2009.\n\n[2] K. W. Church and P. Hanks, Word Association Norms,\n\n Mutual Information, And Lexicography, Computational Linguistics 16 (1990), no. 1, 22\u201329.2", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 4604, "end_char_idx": 4880, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}}, "docstore/metadata": {"b2c614c7-5a4f-49b7-9ea6-bf395bd55e4a": {"doc_hash": "77b18b3e42ae627d7177fc8bd343345f713c1090963b3580245310358e927403", "ref_doc_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719"}, "d507f61b-5023-4281-b391-f307985b8589": {"doc_hash": "3f38603e963b52ecc4bce331dc7eeb04972fbd35f6b856d0f2e273d5da297599", "ref_doc_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719"}, "a21ef176-da5c-464d-b043-b4614032a257": {"doc_hash": "3059e3a5c2ee07d683430e5962441d579bec1abfc30649130aad20a6a4da3537", "ref_doc_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719"}, "43b76dd5-4d0d-43ef-a5ae-cabdb80b8b7e": {"doc_hash": "a483f2aac548a6473edc5e9504de9b11a0d82d97d2e28678c2fd30c3afa6cce4", "ref_doc_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719"}, "41ab694d-c48b-4b70-9faa-d59aa3a2b8c9": {"doc_hash": "b21a61ef597430a09574332f34021b705e40da7237af370dc1ec0b421a1a0e26", "ref_doc_id": "27d0ccb4-550f-4579-9216-012b70e25719"}, "99e39dc0-2dfa-4377-8f7e-8a7